metadata.name: Blotto! #501
metadata.description:
Vanilla JS + SVG
November 2022

Edition of 365

The starting point for this piece was an attempt to simulate the effect of dropping coloured inks or paints onto wet or dry paper ("blots") by combining mixed gradients and various levels of svg filters. I then added stroke and fine line drawings to the blots and played around with rotation and opacity and leaving blanks in the grids. 

The results range from minimal smooth circles, sometimes fading away into the background, to noisy splashes or clouds.

The defined features of the project are:

Blot palettes: 9+n (1 is generated randomly)
Blotting paper: 6 colours
Blot grid: 5 layouts (1x1, 3x3, 5x5, 10x10, 20x20)
Blot stroke: true/false
Blot blanks: true/false
Blotted lines: true/false
Blotulence! (extra turbulence): true/false

To save a PNG file, press "P" or save an SVG by pressing "S"

This project has been tested and works in Chrome, Brave, Edge and Firefox (a little slower on the latter, so please be patient). It does not work in Safari or on IOS at this time.

// PRIMARY SALES
If/when the project mints out, 50% of primary will be donated to Girls Who Code Canada (https://girlswhocode.com/en-ca) and the other 50% to Breakfast Club Canada and I will post the donation receipts on the fx(hash) Discord as well as on my Twitter & genart.social.

metadata.name: Unfolded #180
metadata.description:
A plane is repeatedly folded over itself, choosing creases either at random, or according to some pattern (like a grid). These creases form the boundaries of the individual textured tiles.

Once the folds are complete, they are undone in reverse order, recreating the original plane. With each unfolding, the orientation of each crease (as a mountain or a valley), and each tile (facing up or down) is recorded as a sequence of 1s and 0s. Tiles are colored and textured according to similarities in these binary sequences, giving rise to subtle symmetries and repetitions.

Written in vanilla JS & HTML5 Canvas.

Licensed under CC BY-NC-SA 4.0

metadata.name: Extrusion - v2 #17
metadata.description:
Dear collectors,
Extrusion was originally published as Project #14512 on June 9, 2022.
(https://www.fxhash.xyz/generative/14512)
Due to a technical issue, Project #14512 has been hidden from the site and is being replaced by this reissued version.

_______________________________

Extrusion is a work that brings the generation of particles that perform smooth sinusoidal movements according to the evolution of the animation frames. Each frame registers its position with a slight shading, and with continuous stacking we get the impression of depth that I like to call 'pseudo-3D'.
The perception of movement is something that I really enjoy watching and I hope it can have the same effect on collectors and enthusiasts of animated arts. Even so, for those who prefer static art, the work is finished after a frame count (which may vary depending on its hash) by adding a grain texture followed by a thin black beveled frame with white passe-partout for better highlighting. the post-animation result.

The palette sets were carefully chosen, totaling 19 palettes with 6 colors each, separated into themes of environment, mood, styles, materials and other elements. Of these seven are monochromatic sets with a small rarity of being obtained.

The shapes of the particles vary between 8 pointed stars (rare), circles and vertical or horizontal bars and their trail changes a lot according to the frame count and total number of objects in the scene. Sometimes they look like they are dancing while moving around creating pseudo-three-dimensional objects.

The screens can be obtained in three different aspect ratios: 1x1 (square, more common), and two wide options (16x9 landscape and 9x16 portrait, a little rarer).

As already said and I always say: carefully chosen palettes!

_______________________________
Variety of editions is guaranteed by several features:
* Black or white backgrounds (for better highlighting of particles);
* 19 color palettes with 6 colors each where the rarest is BW (<6%)
* 3 aspect ratios: 1x1 (50%), 9x16 (25%) and 16x9 (25%)
* Controlled variety of scale;
* Controlled variety of particle number;
* Animation time;
* Shape type: circles (60%), bars (30%) and stars (10%);
* Animation with coordinated movement (12%);
* Super rare inverted move (5%)

_______________________________
Interactive instructions:
* Press [I] to change the inverted mode, if you have it.

_______________________________
Saving your .png file:
* Press [S] to save your .png file in screen size;
* Press [0] to save your .png file in qHD resolution;
* Press [1] to save your .png file in FHD resolution;
* Press [2] to save your .png file in UHD (4K) resolution;
* Press [3] to save your .png file in FUHD (8K) resolution;
(for higher resolutions, please wait up for few seconds until complete render)


Made with p5.js
_______________________________

metadata.name: Coronado #356
metadata.description:
This series is about the beauty and charm of imperfection, chaos amidst order, and letting go. It's about knowing that however much control we think we may have, things can all fall apart or burst into something unexpectedly wonderful at any moment, even without our hands tightly on the reigns.

Please see fxtext article linked from main project page for more background on the project and rendering notes.

Some key commands in live mode:

G : Toggle grain
S : Save current resolution
1 : 4000x5000
2 : 6000x7500
3 : 8000x10000
4 : 10000x12500
5 : 12000x15000
6 : 14000x17500
(1-6 work best on Chrome)
(rendering takes longer as resolution increases)

metadata.name: EDDY #158
metadata.description:
An eddy is a circular movement of water counter to a main current. It reminds me of innovations in art, like a small countercurrent to the mainstream, surfacing new techniques and aesthetics. 

I hope that EDDY will brighten your days with its playful swirl of colors, inspired by the sea, the sky, the birds, and post-impressionist paintings.

Keyboard Controls:
[F] Fill the window.
[S] Save the current view in live mode as an image (default 1125x1500px).
[1] [2] [4] [6] Change resolution, 1.5K to 9K.
[R] Reverse course.

Made with p5js and shaders.

Created by elsif, 2022.12.

metadata.name: gradient descent #191
metadata.description:
Whether by choice or circumstance, we often find our lives thrust into uncertainty. We're resilient, though ‚Äî we find patterns in the chaos, deciphering and unraveling it piece by piece until a new comfort emerges. `gradient descent` is my expression of that cyclical flow that comes to dominate our lives.

The piece starts with comfort, a smooth gradient chosen from a curated palette. As the animation runs, that gradient is mutated by a unique sequence of linear transformations - slice, skew or stride on an underlying grid - as it descends into uncertainty. After a time the animation will reverse, peeling back each transformation and returning to comfort before beginning anew.

The menu - which can be accessed with a double click or Escape - gives you extensive control of the experience. I'd encourage you to explore these settings ‚Äî they transform the feel of the piece, allowing you to adapt it to match your environment or mood. Any setting that can be changed in the menu can also be provided as a URL parameter - there's a button in the menu to export them all.

Built with raw WebGL 1.0, optimised to run smoothly on most devices.

Best viewed in full screen on large format displays.

||| controls

[hold space] ‚áù speed up
[esc/2xclick] ‚áù toggle menu
[g] ‚áù toggle gallery mode
[p] ‚áù toggle pause
[s] ‚áù capture current frame
[a] ‚áù capture all keyframes
[8/9/0/-] ‚áù change viewport

||| settings

All settings are configurable via the interactive menu. Initial values can be set as url parameters by adding &[name]=[value] to the url.

loop [1|0, default 1]
|  ‚áù  loop the animation
infinite [1|0, default 0]
|  ‚áù  generate a new sequence after each descent, constantly evolving
gallery [1|0, default 0]
|  ‚áù  display in gallery mode with keyframes
quality [#, default 1]
|  ‚áù  additional dpr scaling - lower to improve animation smoothness
speed [#, default 1]
|  ‚áù  multiplier for step animation speed
step-pause [#, default 0.35]
|  ‚áù  seconds to pause between keyframe steps
start-pause [#, default 4]
|  ‚áù  seconds to pause at the initial keyframe
end-pause [#, default 4]
|  ‚áù  seconds to pause at the final keyframe

||| capture

Capture current frame saves the still immediately, while capture all keyframes saves each of the keyframes sequentially. Some browsers may require confirmation to save multiple stills. When triggered early, unrendered keyframes will be blank. All captures are impacted by the following settings.

capture-aspect [#, default 1]
|  ‚áù  aspect ratio of the capture, as width/height
capture-size [#, default 2048]
|  ‚áù  longest dimension of the captures to save, in pixels
